The better world is already here.
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have been discussing the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world where more people mean less food, where increasing resource demands lead to overexploitation and war, and where the growing production capacity of the last decades is followed by more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, continues to influence the environmental movement today.
The optimists, however, claim that everything will get better - human health, the standard of living, environmental quality and so on.
They are seen by their opponents as "economists of abundance," who trust the market, which allegedly solves all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see if the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this is what I tried to achieve by developing a ranking list of the last 150 years in collaboration with 21 of the world's leading economists.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender ratio, air pollution, climate change and biodiversity – economists have answered the same question: How high were the relative costs of this problem in every year from 1900 to 2013, including forecasts until 2050.
Using classical economic evaluations of all factors of fatalities, health damage, and illiteracy from the destruction of wetlands to higher hurricane risks caused by global warming, economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the extent of the problem, it is compared to the resources available for its solution.
This way the size of the problem becomes clear as a share of the GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's consider the inequality of the sexes.
In effect, we excluded nearly half of the world's population from production.
In 1900, only 15% of the global workforce were of the female sex.
What are the losses that have arisen from this small share?
Even when we consider the higher costs of educating women and that someone has to do the unpaid domestic work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the global GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female employment share and smaller income gaps, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It will likely come as a big surprise that the climate change from 1900 to 2025 is likely to bring a growing net benefit, which grows to 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it only occurs moderately, the benefit prevails.
On the one hand, the higher entries of CO2 were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
A moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand more strongly than it creates new cooling demand, corresponding to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other side, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems like wetlands, corresponding to a loss of about 0.1%.
At further rising temperatures, however, the costs rise and the benefits fall, which dramatically reduces the net benefit.
By 2070, global warming will cause net savings for the world, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the rating list also shows us that the world's biggest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into perspective.
Today more than three million people die in a year from indoor air pollution due to hazardous emissions from cooking and heating. This is equivalent to a 3% loss of the world's GDP.
But in the year 1900, these costs accounted for 19% of the GDP, and it is expected that they will decline to 1% by 2050.
Health indicators have improved the most all over the world.
Until the late 18th century, human lifespan had hardly changed.
The magnitude of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At the time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and probably 76 years by 2050).
The greatest influencer was the decline in infant mortality.
For example, as late as 1970, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which has led to the rescue of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved through world peace throughout the 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have committed more than $2.5 billion for vaccines and have promised a further $10 billion.
Through efforts of Rotary clubs, the World Health Organization, and many others, polio cases have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century were an astonishing 32% of the world's GDP.
They have dropped to about 11% today and will halve again by 2050.
Even if optimists are not correct on all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and much more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of the GDP.
And the general trend is even clearer.
In comparison to the resources available to combat them, global problems have dramatically declined.
Of course, this doesn't mean that there are no problems anymore.
Even though they have decreased in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality and international trade, they are still quite large.
But realists should get used to the thought that the world has greatly improved.
In addition, the rating list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not orient our view on the future towards the most horrific stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather towards objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
